  "output": "No frontend or DB yet — only Python core exists. Issues are all engine-level.\n\n---\n\n## Performance Analysis: `core/`\n\n### 1. Double-traversal in `advance_shipments` — O(2n)\n\n`order_processor.py:7-13` iterates `incoming_shipments` twice per player per round: once to sum arrivals, once to rebuild the list.\n\n```python\n# current — two passes\narrived = sum(s.quantity for s in ps.incoming_shipments if s.arrives_in_rounds == 1)\nps.incoming_shipments = [\n    IncomingShipment(quantity=s.quantity, arrives_in_rounds=s.arrives_in_rounds - 1)\n    for s in ps.incoming_shipments if s.arrives_in_rounds > 1\n]\n\n# fix — one pass, no new object allocation\narrived = 0\nremaining = []\nfor s in ps.incoming_shipments:\n    if s.arrives_in_rounds == 1:\n        arrived += s.quantity\n    else:\n        s.arrives_in_rounds -= 1  # Pydantic v2 models are mutable by default\n        remaining.append(s)\nps.incoming_shipments = remaining\nps.inventory += arrived\n```\n\n### 2. Unnecessary `IncomingShipment` object creation every round\n\nCurrent code allocates a new `IncomingShipment` Pydantic model per in-transit item per round. With `shipping_delay=2` and 4 players over 26 rounds that's ~520 wasted allocations. Fix is the same mutation above.\n\n### 3. `incoming_orders` list is a memory leak\n\n`player.py:37` / `order_processor.py:72` — orders are appended every round but **never consumed or cleared**. After 26 rounds each player holds 26 stale integers.\n\n```python\n# place_orders: after appending, clear old entries\nupstream_ps.incoming_orders.append(order_qty)\n# OR: just keep last N, or use a deque with maxlen\n```\n\nOr clear it at round end in `process_round`:\n```python\n# game_engine.py, after place_orders:\nfor ps in state.players.values():\n    ps.incoming_orders.clear()\n```\n\n### 4. `PlayerState.round_cost()` uses hardcoded constants, diverges from config\n\n`game.py:42`:\n```python\ndef round_cost(self) -> float:\n    return self.inventory * HOLDING_COST_PER_UNIT + self.backlog * BACKLOG_COST_PER_UNIT\n```\n\n`accrue_costs` correctly uses `state.config.holding_cost`/`backlog_cost`. If someone passes a custom `GameConfig`, `round_cost()` silently gives wrong numbers. Either remove the method or pass config:\n\n```python\ndef round_cost(self, config: GameConfig) -> float:\n    return self.inventory * config.holding_cost + self.backlog * config.backlog_cost\n```\n\n### 5. `is_round_complete` rebuilds active-roles set on every call\n\n`game.py:56` — called after each `submit_order`. Creates a new set from a dict comprehension each time.\n\n```python\n# fix: cache on GameState init or compute once per game start\n# simple approach: store as a field\nactive_human_roles: set[PlayerRole] = Field(default_factory=set)\n\n# populated in game_engine.create_game:\nstate.active_human_roles = {r for r in ROLE_ORDER if r not in ai_roles}\n\n# is_round_complete becomes:\ndef is_round_complete(self) -> bool:\n    return self.active_human_roles.issubset(self.orders_this_round)\n```\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| Issue | Location | Impact |\n|---|---|---|\n| Double-traversal + new object per shipment | `order_processor.py:7-13` | CPU + memory each tick |\n| `incoming_orders` grows unbounded | `order_processor.py:72` | Memory leak over game lifetime |\n| `round_cost()` uses stale constants | `game.py:42` | Correctness + silent divergence |\n| `is_round_complete` rebuilds set each call | `game.py:56` | Minor CPU, worth fixing now |\n\nNo N+1 queries or React re-renders — those aren't implemented yet. The `incoming_orders` leak is the only true leak; fix it in `process_round` with a single `.clear()` loop.\n",
